<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-08-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-08-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="389" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d389">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 123.G35/41.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Minister of
                                Cuba</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 57.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-08-28">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 28, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department is in receipt of a
                            telegram from the American Chargé d’Affaires at Habana stating that
                            while entering the Miramar Hotel on the evening of August 27 he was
                            assaulted from behind, without provocation or warning, by a reporter of
                            La Prensa <pb facs="0385" n="269" xml:id="pg_269"/> who had been
                            excluded from the Legation and from the Department of State of Cuba
                            because of false statements and who is said to be notorious as having
                            figured in many unsavory incidents. Mr. Gibson was knocked senseless and
                            while in this condition an attempt was made by the assailant to inflict
                            further injuries.</p>
                        <p>This Department expects the Cuban Government to take prompt and energetic
                            measures adequately to punish the offender.</p>
                        <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>